00:06:04.010 --> 00:06:08.280
So last day we ended with the
stoichiometry, and I showed

00:06:08.280 --> 00:06:11.290
you the Kroll process,
how to make titanium.

00:06:11.290 --> 00:06:16.220
So the question that we never
got to was how do we tell that

00:06:16.220 --> 00:06:19.980
magnesium has a higher affinity
for chlorine than

00:06:19.980 --> 00:06:21.010
titanium does?

00:06:21.010 --> 00:06:24.130
How do we know that magnesium
is going to reduce titanium

00:06:24.130 --> 00:06:26.490
tetrachloride to a sponge?

00:06:26.490 --> 00:06:29.290
So for that we have to
look inside the atom.

00:06:29.290 --> 00:06:30.590
We have to look inside
the atom.

00:06:30.590 --> 00:06:32.510
So that's what we're going
to start doing today.

00:06:32.510 --> 00:06:34.400
And we're going to begin,
as often we will,

00:06:34.400 --> 00:06:35.390
with a history lesson.

00:06:35.390 --> 00:06:38.680
So let's go back for a status
report around the end of the

00:06:38.680 --> 00:06:39.650
19th century.

00:06:39.650 --> 00:06:42.740
So what did we know towards the
end of the 19th century?

00:06:42.740 --> 00:06:46.460
The atom is electrically
neutral.

00:06:46.460 --> 00:06:51.802
The negative charge is
carried by electrons.

00:06:51.802 --> 00:06:57.350
We knew that there was some
carrier of negative charge.

00:06:57.350 --> 00:07:01.850
We knew further that this
electron is very, very tiny.

00:07:01.850 --> 00:07:03.870
Small mass.

00:07:03.870 --> 00:07:07.580
And so if it has a very small
mass, then by difference, then

00:07:07.580 --> 00:07:10.560
the bulk of the mass of atom
must be contained in the

00:07:10.560 --> 00:07:13.330
positive charge.

00:07:13.330 --> 00:07:16.860
So now the question is, what is
the spatial distribution of

00:07:16.860 --> 00:07:17.930
charge inside an atom?

00:07:17.930 --> 00:07:19.440
You might say, well why do
we want to know that?

00:07:19.440 --> 00:07:22.930
Well, we're trying to get a
physical model of the atom so

00:07:22.930 --> 00:07:24.980
that then we can start to
address the question of

00:07:24.980 --> 00:07:26.410
chemical reactivity.

00:07:26.410 --> 00:07:29.130
So we have got to know where all
the players are before we

00:07:29.130 --> 00:07:31.370
can attribute action to them.

00:07:31.370 --> 00:07:34.720
So let's now take a look
at models of the atom.

00:07:34.720 --> 00:07:40.330
For the first modern model
of the atom we go to J.

00:07:40.330 --> 00:07:40.570
J.

00:07:40.570 --> 00:07:41.820
Thompson.

00:07:44.430 --> 00:07:44.710
J.

00:07:44.710 --> 00:07:44.940
J.

00:07:44.940 --> 00:07:48.590
Thompson, he was a professor of
physics and director of the

00:07:48.590 --> 00:07:51.566
Cavendish lab at Cambridge
University.

00:08:11.530 --> 00:08:13.170
The other Cambridge.

00:08:13.170 --> 00:08:15.480
Cambridge University.

00:08:15.480 --> 00:08:19.620
And this Cavendish Lab was named
after Henry Cavendish.

00:08:19.620 --> 00:08:21.640
The same one who is credited
with the discovery

00:08:21.640 --> 00:08:24.060
of hydrogen in 1766.

00:08:24.060 --> 00:08:27.500
He never married, and when he
died he bequeathed this

00:08:27.500 --> 00:08:30.920
fortune to Cambridge University,
and they took that

00:08:30.920 --> 00:08:34.060
money and established a physics
laboratory, which is

00:08:34.060 --> 00:08:36.110
still in operation
to this day.

00:08:36.110 --> 00:08:39.380
So what did J.

00:08:39.380 --> 00:08:39.570
J.

00:08:39.570 --> 00:08:40.430
Thompson tell us?

00:08:40.430 --> 00:08:44.580
He said the electrons were
distributed throughout a

00:08:44.580 --> 00:08:48.360
uniformly charged positive
sphere of atomic dimensions.

00:09:17.240 --> 00:09:18.410
So that's the text.

00:09:18.410 --> 00:09:22.500
Now let's make this cartoon,
because that makes more sense.

00:09:22.500 --> 00:09:23.920
Visualize it a little
bit better.

00:09:23.920 --> 00:09:26.320
So it looks a little
bit like this.

00:09:26.320 --> 00:09:32.350
So here's a sphere of
atomic dimension.

00:09:32.350 --> 00:09:37.570
Electrons are these tiny little
things distributed

00:09:37.570 --> 00:09:41.130
throughout the positive
sphere.

00:09:44.350 --> 00:09:47.570
And this is massive because
the electrons have

00:09:47.570 --> 00:09:49.940
very, very low mass.

00:09:49.940 --> 00:09:53.530
And just to be clear, there
are no protons.

00:09:53.530 --> 00:09:54.660
No protons.

00:09:54.660 --> 00:09:55.740
So this isn't positive.

00:09:55.740 --> 00:09:57.440
It's a positive chargeness.

00:09:57.440 --> 00:10:00.240
It's just a big positive blur.

00:10:00.240 --> 00:10:02.140
And then the little
electrons inside.

00:10:02.140 --> 00:10:12.010
So the electrons are negative,
and they're tiny and low-mass,

00:10:12.010 --> 00:10:13.260
and they're mobile.

00:10:15.200 --> 00:10:17.450
He didn't say much about how
they move, but you can imagine

00:10:17.450 --> 00:10:19.870
that they move, and maybe
they even spin.

00:10:19.870 --> 00:10:20.540
And so on.

00:10:20.540 --> 00:10:22.820
And this was known as the
Plum Pudding Model.

00:10:27.555 --> 00:10:30.550
There's a big cultural
bias here.

00:10:30.550 --> 00:10:33.610
So even though I grew up in
British Canada, I never had

00:10:33.610 --> 00:10:34.950
this stuff.

00:10:34.950 --> 00:10:38.540
But my understanding is plum
pudding is this dish that's

00:10:38.540 --> 00:10:41.620
served at holidays and
Christmas-time.

00:10:41.620 --> 00:10:45.660
So the custard is the charge,
the positive charge.

00:10:45.660 --> 00:10:50.010
And these little bits of fruit
are the electrons.

00:10:50.010 --> 00:10:50.650
And they're throughout.

00:10:50.650 --> 00:10:51.970
At Christmas-time, they
might even put

00:10:51.970 --> 00:10:52.930
little charms in here.

00:10:52.930 --> 00:10:55.910
Like a little wishbone or
something for good luck.

00:10:55.910 --> 00:10:58.510
And you pull it out and all
that kind of stuff.

00:10:58.510 --> 00:11:02.080
Yeah that's merry,
old England.

00:11:02.080 --> 00:11:04.370
So this is the Plum
Pudding Model.

00:11:04.370 --> 00:11:06.080
And that's what was in place.

00:11:06.080 --> 00:11:09.150
By the way, we've been using
the term electron, but J.

00:11:09.150 --> 00:11:09.880
J.

00:11:09.880 --> 00:11:11.630
did not like the
term electron.

00:11:11.630 --> 00:11:15.090
Actually, he won his Nobel
Prize for the-- quote,

00:11:15.090 --> 00:11:17.160
unquote-- the discovery
of the electron.

00:11:17.160 --> 00:11:19.800
Just as Cavendish didn't
discover hydrogen, he

00:11:19.800 --> 00:11:21.020
characterized it.

00:11:21.020 --> 00:11:21.270
J.

00:11:21.270 --> 00:11:21.460
J.

00:11:21.460 --> 00:11:23.560
Thompson characterized
the electron.

00:11:23.560 --> 00:11:25.630
What did he in particular
characterize?

00:11:25.630 --> 00:11:27.890
He characterized the
charge-to-mass ratio.

00:11:27.890 --> 00:11:30.930
He made the first quantitative
measure of the charge-to-mass

00:11:30.930 --> 00:11:32.180
ratio of the electron.

00:11:32.180 --> 00:11:34.210
But he never used the
term, electron.

00:11:34.210 --> 00:11:35.550
He called it the corpuscle.

00:11:48.260 --> 00:11:53.190
He called it the corpuscle of
electrical charge, whereas

00:11:53.190 --> 00:11:57.700
this is really sort of
an elementary charge.

00:11:57.700 --> 00:11:58.970
The corpuscle.

00:11:58.970 --> 00:12:05.500
And fortunately there was
another British chemist. In

00:12:05.500 --> 00:12:08.070
fact, he was an electrochemist.
His name was

00:12:08.070 --> 00:12:13.230
John Stoney, who, while I think
that Thompson was a

00:12:13.230 --> 00:12:17.420
brilliant man, I wasn't crazy
about his literary choices.

00:12:17.420 --> 00:12:21.420
And it was Stoney who said,
let's call the term electron,

00:12:21.420 --> 00:12:25.050
coming from the Greek term,
elektra, which is the Greek

00:12:25.050 --> 00:12:26.040
word for amber.

00:12:26.040 --> 00:12:28.810
And you know if you rub amber,
you'll build up static

00:12:28.810 --> 00:12:31.880
charge, and so on.

00:12:31.880 --> 00:12:34.730
That's where we got
the electron from.

00:12:34.730 --> 00:12:38.000
So that looks pretty good.

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:41.450
So that's our theory.

00:12:41.450 --> 00:12:43.670
And what happens next?

00:12:43.670 --> 00:12:47.130
Well, what happens next is that
we've got to put this

00:12:47.130 --> 00:12:49.530
theory to the test. And the
person who puts the theory to

00:12:49.530 --> 00:12:52.285
the test is a man by the name
of Ernest Rutherford.

00:12:56.680 --> 00:12:58.350
Rutherford was an interesting
character.

00:12:58.350 --> 00:13:02.530
He came from New Zealand and
he was born on a farm.

00:13:02.530 --> 00:13:04.990
It was a family with
12 children.

00:13:04.990 --> 00:13:07.580
You notice Mendeleyev came from
a family of 14, this guy

00:13:07.580 --> 00:13:09.750
comes from a family of 12.

00:13:09.750 --> 00:13:12.680
So you learn how to survive.

00:13:12.680 --> 00:13:16.170
He worked on a farm so he was
very handy, and that came in

00:13:16.170 --> 00:13:20.010
to play as his career
progressed.

00:13:20.010 --> 00:13:22.080
He was a brilliant
experimentalist. He was able

00:13:22.080 --> 00:13:24.870
to do experiments where
others failed.

00:13:24.870 --> 00:13:32.400
And he did this experiment where
he was a professor of

00:13:32.400 --> 00:13:42.840
physics at Victoria University
in Manchester in the UK.

00:13:47.670 --> 00:13:52.570
Now, he came out of New Zealand,
got a scholarship to

00:13:52.570 --> 00:13:54.920
study at Cambridge University.

00:13:54.920 --> 00:13:57.340
And he was actually a research
student for J.

00:13:57.340 --> 00:13:57.540
J.

00:13:57.540 --> 00:13:58.530
Thompson.

00:13:58.530 --> 00:14:01.720
And he conducted his thesis
research under J.

00:14:01.720 --> 00:14:02.500
J.

00:14:02.500 --> 00:14:07.250
and during that time his thesis
research was about the

00:14:07.250 --> 00:14:09.125
properties of charged
particles.

00:14:19.270 --> 00:14:24.200
And they were very interested
in gases and radioactive

00:14:24.200 --> 00:14:26.500
elements, ionizing radiation,
the whole thing.

00:14:26.500 --> 00:14:30.070
The Cavendish lab was a
beehive of activity.

00:14:30.070 --> 00:14:34.670
And what he did under his PhD
was he understood both the

00:14:34.670 --> 00:14:37.080
alpha particle and the
beta particle.

00:14:37.080 --> 00:14:39.100
First, he identified
what they are.

00:14:39.100 --> 00:14:41.040
The alpha particle
was determined to

00:14:41.040 --> 00:14:42.780
be the helium nucleus.

00:14:42.780 --> 00:14:45.700
So this is helium that's lost
both of its electrons.

00:14:45.700 --> 00:14:49.000
So it's just protons and
neutrons in the nucleus.

00:14:49.000 --> 00:14:49.930
Completely naked.

00:14:49.930 --> 00:14:51.050
No electrons.

00:14:51.050 --> 00:14:54.380
And then the beta particle,
which other people in physics

00:14:54.380 --> 00:14:57.240
had been referring to this
mysterious beta particle, he

00:14:57.240 --> 00:14:58.850
made the connection
between the beta

00:14:58.850 --> 00:15:00.080
particle and the electron.

00:15:00.080 --> 00:15:03.220
So the same electron that's over
here and attributed to

00:15:03.220 --> 00:15:06.580
the negative charge within the
nucleus is also a free

00:15:06.580 --> 00:15:08.060
particle that can go
through space.

00:15:08.060 --> 00:15:10.190
And these are taken
from your reading.

00:15:10.190 --> 00:15:15.360
And you can see that if you send
the particle beam through

00:15:15.360 --> 00:15:19.120
a charged plate, the negative
plate here being the lower

00:15:19.120 --> 00:15:21.830
plate, the positive particle,
which in this case is the

00:15:21.830 --> 00:15:25.940
alpha particle, will bend down
towards the negative plate.

00:15:25.940 --> 00:15:28.740
And the negative particle, being
the free electron, is

00:15:28.740 --> 00:15:30.680
bent in the opposite
direction.

00:15:30.680 --> 00:15:32.710
So these are the kinds of
experiments they would do.

00:15:32.710 --> 00:15:34.730
And they also looked
at their ability to

00:15:34.730 --> 00:15:37.600
penetrate different media.

00:15:37.600 --> 00:15:46.905
So when it comes to their
ability to penetrate solids,

00:15:46.905 --> 00:15:48.500
they differentiate themselves.

00:15:48.500 --> 00:15:51.760
So they alpha particle
is quite poor

00:15:51.760 --> 00:15:53.020
at penetrating solids.

00:15:53.020 --> 00:15:55.230
So you see in the cartoon there,
the alpha particle is

00:15:55.230 --> 00:15:58.600
stopped even by that little
sheet of paper.

00:15:58.600 --> 00:16:02.610
So it doesn't do so well here,
whereas the beta particle, the

00:16:02.610 --> 00:16:05.760
electron, can go zooming right
through the paper and is

00:16:05.760 --> 00:16:08.040
stopped by the lead.

00:16:08.040 --> 00:16:10.860
And then over here they were
also studying their ability to

00:16:10.860 --> 00:16:12.690
ionize gases.

00:16:12.690 --> 00:16:15.190
So if you take a gas and you
bombard it with alpha

00:16:15.190 --> 00:16:17.230
particles, will you get
a lot of ionization?

00:16:17.230 --> 00:16:19.150
Yes or no, et cetera.

00:16:19.150 --> 00:16:22.830
And what they found was that it
was a complementary, that

00:16:22.830 --> 00:16:26.150
the alpha particle is pretty
good at ionizing gases,

00:16:26.150 --> 00:16:29.900
whereas the beta particle is
poor at ionizing gases, and in

00:16:29.900 --> 00:16:30.680
fact, is stopped.

00:16:30.680 --> 00:16:32.220
This is why, if you
have an electron

00:16:32.220 --> 00:16:33.320
beam you need a vacuum.

00:16:33.320 --> 00:16:36.380
Otherwise, the electron will
be dissipated in very, very

00:16:36.380 --> 00:16:37.440
short order.

00:16:37.440 --> 00:16:39.130
So after doing this
work with J.

00:16:39.130 --> 00:16:42.660
J., he got a teaching job
in Canada at McGill

00:16:42.660 --> 00:16:44.770
University up north.

00:16:44.770 --> 00:16:48.530
And while he was there he
continued to do work on the

00:16:48.530 --> 00:16:52.510
origin of alpha particles and
won the Nobel Prize for his

00:16:52.510 --> 00:16:54.800
work while he was at McGill.

00:16:54.800 --> 00:17:01.380
And so when he determined that
the alpha particle origin in

00:17:01.380 --> 00:17:13.720
the decomposition, the
disintegration of elements.

00:17:13.720 --> 00:17:19.300
And believe it or not, in this
work back in 1906, 1907, he

00:17:19.300 --> 00:17:23.530
was already anticipating nuclear
fission because he was

00:17:23.530 --> 00:17:28.080
saying that if you put thorium
or polonium into a tube, you

00:17:28.080 --> 00:17:30.610
can expect that it will
emit alpha particles.

00:17:30.610 --> 00:17:33.150
Well, conservation of mass
says they have got to be

00:17:33.150 --> 00:17:34.080
coming from somewhere.

00:17:34.080 --> 00:17:36.450
And if they're not coming from
out here, they have got to be

00:17:36.450 --> 00:17:37.620
coming from inside.

00:17:37.620 --> 00:17:38.670
This was brilliant work.

00:17:38.670 --> 00:17:42.930
This is Rutherford, young man
in Montreal, gets the Nobel

00:17:42.930 --> 00:17:44.730
Prize in 1908.

00:17:44.730 --> 00:17:49.930
And then he goes to Victoria
University, and he sets up

00:17:49.930 --> 00:17:51.640
this experiment.

00:17:51.640 --> 00:17:53.760
Critical experiment.

00:17:53.760 --> 00:17:54.940
I mean, imagine this guy.

00:17:54.940 --> 00:17:56.550
I mean, he's already got
the Nobel Prize.

00:17:56.550 --> 00:17:58.670
He could just put his feet up.

00:17:58.670 --> 00:17:59.590
No, he keeps going.

00:17:59.590 --> 00:18:00.610
So this is the experiment.

00:18:00.610 --> 00:18:02.740
It's called the
Rutherford-Geiger-Marsden

00:18:02.740 --> 00:18:03.650
experiment.

00:18:03.650 --> 00:18:06.340
Because Rutherford was the
brains behind it and Geiger

00:18:06.340 --> 00:18:08.060
and Marsden were the
guys in the lab.

00:18:08.060 --> 00:18:09.390
And so here's the experiment.

00:18:09.390 --> 00:18:12.670
So what he's going to do is he's
going to put this model

00:18:12.670 --> 00:18:15.370
to the test. We're going
to see if this model

00:18:15.370 --> 00:18:16.690
makes sense or not.

00:18:16.690 --> 00:18:19.270
So he's got a gold foil-- now
they used different elements,

00:18:19.270 --> 00:18:22.430
but ultimately they loved gold
because gold, first of all, is

00:18:22.430 --> 00:18:23.800
noble and it doesn't oxide.

00:18:23.800 --> 00:18:27.830
So it's pure, even in
atmospheric oxygen.

00:18:27.830 --> 00:18:30.450
And secondly, we've known
since antiquity we can

00:18:30.450 --> 00:18:33.030
physically deform gold and
make it into something

00:18:33.030 --> 00:18:34.830
sub-paper thin.

00:18:34.830 --> 00:18:35.610
So that's what they did.

00:18:35.610 --> 00:18:39.670
They beat this thing
down to 600

00:18:39.670 --> 00:18:41.990
nanometers thick, 0.6 micron.

00:18:41.990 --> 00:18:46.610
And they used alpha
particles here.

00:18:46.610 --> 00:18:49.840
Radium, polonium, thorium as
the source in the lead

00:18:49.840 --> 00:18:50.890
container and so on.

00:18:50.890 --> 00:18:54.330
And this stream of alpha
particles comes zooming out at

00:18:54.330 --> 00:18:59.450
energies of 7.68 million
electron volts per particle.

00:18:59.450 --> 00:19:04.930
So this is like a cannon with
a pumpkin in front of it.

00:19:04.930 --> 00:19:09.610
And they're going to shoot
these at the foil.

00:19:09.610 --> 00:19:11.280
So what's the purpose here?

00:19:11.280 --> 00:19:12.610
They want to see what's
going on.

00:19:12.610 --> 00:19:16.230
And if you imagine that we are
shooting alpha particles,

00:19:16.230 --> 00:19:20.410
which are positive, and I've
got a wall here of all of

00:19:20.410 --> 00:19:24.250
these nuclei that are
essentially positive

00:19:24.250 --> 00:19:27.780
chargeness, uniformly
distributed with these tiny,

00:19:27.780 --> 00:19:30.980
tiny little electrons of almost
no mass, you'd expect

00:19:30.980 --> 00:19:33.090
that most of these particles are
just going to go zooming

00:19:33.090 --> 00:19:34.350
on through.

00:19:34.350 --> 00:19:37.800
Beyond a certain thickness,
I might start seeing some

00:19:37.800 --> 00:19:38.650
attenuation.

00:19:38.650 --> 00:19:41.010
But if I get the gold film
really thin, I should just go

00:19:41.010 --> 00:19:42.820
blasting these all through.

00:19:42.820 --> 00:19:44.510
Well, what they find
is, two things.

00:19:44.510 --> 00:19:47.260
First of all, most of the
particles do go through.

00:19:47.260 --> 00:19:49.450
When they go through, they're
deflected a little bit.

00:19:49.450 --> 00:19:51.870
They don't just go through,
they are deflected.

00:19:51.870 --> 00:19:54.220
And most of them are deflected
through low angles.

00:19:54.220 --> 00:19:58.020
But a small number of them are
deflected through high angles.

00:19:58.020 --> 00:20:00.190
They almost go straight
back at the source.

00:20:03.450 --> 00:20:07.790
So if you've got that set of
data, that doesn't support

00:20:07.790 --> 00:20:09.480
this model.

00:20:09.480 --> 00:20:13.950
This model cannot be sustained
in the light of those data.

00:20:13.950 --> 00:20:15.180
It's a very important
experiment.

00:20:15.180 --> 00:20:16.560
By the way, how do they
count these things?

00:20:16.560 --> 00:20:18.420
Well, Geiger is the
same guy who give

00:20:18.420 --> 00:20:19.620
us the Geiger counter.

00:20:19.620 --> 00:20:24.320
Geiger was a technician that
worked for Rutherford.

00:20:24.320 --> 00:20:26.710
And he developed this screen,
they called it a

00:20:26.710 --> 00:20:27.650
scintillation screen.

00:20:27.650 --> 00:20:30.590
It was coated with
zinc sulfide.

00:20:30.590 --> 00:20:34.050
And so when alpha particles
bounced and they hit the

00:20:34.050 --> 00:20:37.560
screen, they would excite
electrons in the screen and

00:20:37.560 --> 00:20:40.690
then cause a scintilla,
a spark.

00:20:40.690 --> 00:20:43.230
And then what you do is you just
get a graduate student or

00:20:43.230 --> 00:20:47.340
some other source of abundant,
cheap labor-- and you have a

00:20:47.340 --> 00:20:49.340
whole bunch of graduate students
sitting here-- and

00:20:49.340 --> 00:20:51.700
they count.

00:20:51.700 --> 00:20:54.980
That's how it was done in
good old days, 1909.

00:20:54.980 --> 00:20:59.190
And so they counted what
the distribution was.

00:20:59.190 --> 00:21:02.206
So that's the experiment.

00:21:07.250 --> 00:21:08.500
So this is taken
from your book.

00:21:08.500 --> 00:21:10.370
So this what you'd expect.

00:21:10.370 --> 00:21:11.520
And this is what they saw.

00:21:11.520 --> 00:21:13.850
So this is small angles and
this is large angles.

00:21:13.850 --> 00:21:17.280
Theaters of the angle here.

00:21:17.280 --> 00:21:18.530
Now Marsden, who's the third?

00:21:18.530 --> 00:21:19.310
There's a third person.

00:21:19.310 --> 00:21:19.980
Marsden.

00:21:19.980 --> 00:21:22.180
Marsden's not too different
from you.

00:21:22.180 --> 00:21:24.120
Marsden was about 20 years
old at the time.

00:21:24.120 --> 00:21:26.565
He dropped out of school and
then he came to Rutherford,

00:21:26.565 --> 00:21:28.640
and he said, I'm looking
for a job.

00:21:28.640 --> 00:21:30.590
In those days, you couldn't
return to college.

00:21:30.590 --> 00:21:32.260
If you dropped out, finished.

00:21:32.260 --> 00:21:33.910
You had to stay all
the way through.

00:21:33.910 --> 00:21:36.380
Once you dropped out, they
slam the door behind you.

00:21:36.380 --> 00:21:39.620
But Rutherford, he
was different.

00:21:39.620 --> 00:21:41.090
He looked at people
on the basis of

00:21:41.090 --> 00:21:42.570
their intrinsic value.

00:21:42.570 --> 00:21:44.220
He didn't care about title.

00:21:44.220 --> 00:21:46.640
And so he said to Marsden,
OK, you want to do

00:21:46.640 --> 00:21:47.630
something for me?

00:21:47.630 --> 00:21:54.240
Here's your question, I like you
to imagine an alternative

00:21:54.240 --> 00:21:55.880
model of the atom.

00:21:55.880 --> 00:21:58.460
And here's the alternative
model of the atom.

00:21:58.460 --> 00:22:02.380
What Rutherford said was,
suppose instead, if this is

00:22:02.380 --> 00:22:05.360
the dimension of the atom,
instead of having positive

00:22:05.360 --> 00:22:09.020
charge uniformly distributed,
he said, what if we have

00:22:09.020 --> 00:22:13.340
positive charge concentrated at
one point and then out here

00:22:13.340 --> 00:22:14.730
we have the negative charge?

00:22:14.730 --> 00:22:16.230
So here's the positive charge.

00:22:18.730 --> 00:22:20.525
And here's a whole bunch
of negative charge.

00:22:25.300 --> 00:22:27.480
And now here's the next one.

00:22:27.480 --> 00:22:29.800
And here's the next one.

00:22:29.800 --> 00:22:30.780
And so on.

00:22:30.780 --> 00:22:33.820
And now we're going to shoot
these helium nuclei.

00:22:33.820 --> 00:22:35.130
See what's in between here?

00:22:35.130 --> 00:22:38.500
This is a void, taking
from Democritus.

00:22:38.500 --> 00:22:43.750
And so now if I shoot the
positive helium nuclei here,

00:22:43.750 --> 00:22:45.910
if they get close
to this positive

00:22:45.910 --> 00:22:48.090
charge they'll be deflected.

00:22:48.090 --> 00:22:51.190
If they don't get close to the
positive charge, they just go

00:22:51.190 --> 00:22:53.020
right through.

00:22:53.020 --> 00:22:56.180
And once in awhile they get
almost on axis, in which case

00:22:56.180 --> 00:22:57.600
they fling back.

00:22:57.600 --> 00:23:00.900
This model would be consistent
with the data set I just

00:23:00.900 --> 00:23:01.850
showed you.

00:23:01.850 --> 00:23:05.290
And then to go further, he says
to Marsden, I'm going to

00:23:05.290 --> 00:23:09.140
tell you what the distribution
of high-angle scattering was,

00:23:09.140 --> 00:23:15.320
you tell me what is the ratio
between the radius of the

00:23:15.320 --> 00:23:19.550
nucleus, where the positive
charge is to the-- excuse me,

00:23:19.550 --> 00:23:22.520
I'm showing you the diameter, so
this is the diameter of the

00:23:22.520 --> 00:23:26.570
nucleus versus the diameter
of the atom.

00:23:26.570 --> 00:23:29.310
What would be the ratio
of the two?

00:23:29.310 --> 00:23:33.910
I mean, it's gold, so I know
I got 79 plus here.

00:23:33.910 --> 00:23:35.580
And I've got 2 plus.

00:23:35.580 --> 00:23:36.880
And I've got a 79 plus.

00:23:36.880 --> 00:23:41.720
What would be the size of the
sphere of 79 plus that would

00:23:41.720 --> 00:23:45.250
deflect something of 2 plus
through this angle?

00:23:45.250 --> 00:23:46.160
So that's Marsden.

00:23:46.160 --> 00:23:48.210
It's not bad for a kid that's
been out of school for a

00:23:48.210 --> 00:23:48.820
couple of years.

00:23:48.820 --> 00:23:51.090
That's his problem.

00:23:51.090 --> 00:23:51.650
So he did.

00:23:51.650 --> 00:23:54.580
He did the calculation.

00:23:54.580 --> 00:23:58.710
He did the calculation and
Marsden figured out that the

00:23:58.710 --> 00:24:07.440
radius of the nucleus to the
radius of the atom is on the

00:24:07.440 --> 00:24:12.840
order of about 1 to 10,000.

00:24:12.840 --> 00:24:17.390
That means most of the
gold foil is void.

00:24:17.390 --> 00:24:20.030
Most of the gold foil
is nothing.

00:24:20.030 --> 00:24:23.160
And you've got all this
mass, highly dense,

00:24:23.160 --> 00:24:25.400
concentrated here.

00:24:25.400 --> 00:24:29.270
So this is the Rutherford model,
which was called the

00:24:29.270 --> 00:24:30.520
nuclear model.

00:24:34.370 --> 00:24:37.230
This was proposed by Rutherford
because it has such

00:24:37.230 --> 00:24:38.580
a thing is a nucleus.

00:24:38.580 --> 00:24:41.570
He coined the term, nucleus.

00:24:41.570 --> 00:24:46.500
So that's a big step forward
from this thing here.

00:24:46.500 --> 00:24:51.220
So you'd think that the physics

00:24:51.220 --> 00:24:52.510
community would be ecstatic.

00:24:52.510 --> 00:24:54.570
That now we've got a model that
squares with the data.

00:24:54.570 --> 00:24:57.810
Well, what do you think the
reaction to Rutherford's

00:24:57.810 --> 00:24:59.660
announcement was?

00:24:59.660 --> 00:25:00.660
Condemnation.

00:25:00.660 --> 00:25:02.140
Derision.

00:25:02.140 --> 00:25:03.080
People didn't like it.

00:25:03.080 --> 00:25:03.840
They laughed at him.

00:25:03.840 --> 00:25:06.600
They said, well,
this is crazy.

00:25:06.600 --> 00:25:08.610
There's a couple of problems
with this.

00:25:08.610 --> 00:25:20.270
So strong negative reaction
to Rutherford's model.

00:25:20.270 --> 00:25:24.450
And here the two major
objections that people posed.

00:25:24.450 --> 00:25:28.600
First of all, they talked
about nuclear collapse.

00:25:28.600 --> 00:25:35.530
They said if you've got a system
of negative particles

00:25:35.530 --> 00:25:39.580
revolving around a positive
nucleus, electrostatic forces

00:25:39.580 --> 00:25:42.800
are going to cause them to
be drawn to one another.

00:25:42.800 --> 00:25:45.520
What's going to keep the
electrons from collapsing into

00:25:45.520 --> 00:25:47.060
the nucleus?

00:25:47.060 --> 00:25:49.410
That was the first objection.

00:25:49.410 --> 00:25:51.800
Coulombic attraction.

00:25:51.800 --> 00:25:53.780
Coulombic, electrostatic,
same thing.

00:25:53.780 --> 00:25:55.710
If you want to use a man's
name, Coulombic.

00:25:55.710 --> 00:25:58.740
If you don't want to use a man's
name, electrostatic.

00:25:58.740 --> 00:26:05.930
Coulombic attraction between
plus and minus.

00:26:05.930 --> 00:26:10.560
And the second one was, OK,
suppose for some reason we

00:26:10.560 --> 00:26:14.810
don't understand that the
electron doesn't collapse, it

00:26:14.810 --> 00:26:18.530
stays in orbit, it's still
not going to work.

00:26:18.530 --> 00:26:20.350
Because you run out of energy.

00:26:20.350 --> 00:26:23.320
If you take a charged particle,
a charged particle

00:26:23.320 --> 00:26:26.000
that accelerates consumes
energy.

00:26:26.000 --> 00:26:29.560
Acceleration, as you know, can
mean either change in speed or

00:26:29.560 --> 00:26:30.910
change in direction.

00:26:30.910 --> 00:26:35.660
So if the electron is revolving
at a constant speed,

00:26:35.660 --> 00:26:37.530
it has to change direction;
otherwise, it will

00:26:37.530 --> 00:26:39.040
fly out of the room.

00:26:39.040 --> 00:26:42.160
So changing direction means
acceleration, which means what

00:26:42.160 --> 00:26:44.410
keeps the energy in
the electron?

00:26:44.410 --> 00:26:45.970
Why doesn't the electron
just run out of

00:26:45.970 --> 00:26:48.080
energy and just stop?

00:26:48.080 --> 00:26:50.120
Even if you can prevent
it from collapsing,

00:26:50.120 --> 00:26:52.000
it will just stop.

00:26:52.000 --> 00:26:53.905
So this is the problem
of energy deficit.

00:26:56.420 --> 00:26:58.760
Energy deficit.

00:26:58.760 --> 00:27:00.110
Well, what powers
the electron?

00:27:03.450 --> 00:27:05.405
What powers the accelerating
electron?

00:27:14.290 --> 00:27:15.540
So that's a problem.

00:27:18.320 --> 00:27:20.960
So now the story continues.

00:27:20.960 --> 00:27:23.680
The next chapter is 1912.

00:27:23.680 --> 00:27:25.130
Because this is 1911.

00:27:25.130 --> 00:27:28.420
In 1912, a young Danish
businessman by the name of

00:27:28.420 --> 00:27:31.590
Niels Bohr.

00:27:31.590 --> 00:27:34.770
Niels Bohr just finished his PhD
in Copenhagen and he got a

00:27:34.770 --> 00:27:37.700
fellowship from the Carlsburg
Brewery Foundation.

00:27:37.700 --> 00:27:40.540
Carlsburg Brewery put up
money for science.

00:27:40.540 --> 00:27:43.310
So he won a Carlsburg
fellowship.

